From: conda-forge
Subject: [PATCH] Disable job objects in process library to fix builderMainLoop error

GHC 9.2.8 bundles process-1.6.16.0 which has a bug in Windows job object
handling that causes "builderMainLoop: invalid argument" errors. The bug
was fixed in process-1.6.18.0 but we cannot easily upgrade the bundled library.

This patch makes the createJob() function in the process library's C code
return NULL immediately, effectively disabling job objects. This is safe
because job objects are an optimization for process management, not a
required feature.

The Stage 1 GHC we build will contain this patched process library, so when
it compiles Stage 2 GHC, the builderMainLoop error won't occur.

See:
- https://hackage.haskell.org/package/process-1.6.24.0/changelog
- https://github.com/haskell/cabal/issues/7309

diff --git a/libraries/process/cbits/win32/runProcess.c b/libraries/process/cbits/win32/runProcess.c
--- a/libraries/process/cbits/win32/runProcess.c
+++ b/libraries/process/cbits/win32/runProcess.c
@@ -212,6 +212,12 @@ fail:
 static HANDLE
 createJob ()
 {
+    // CONDA-FORGE: Disable job objects to avoid "builderMainLoop: invalid argument"
+    // errors caused by a bug in process-1.6.16.0 (fixed in 1.6.18.0).
+    // Job objects are an optimization, not required for correct operation.
+    return NULL;
+
+#if 0  // Original code disabled
     HANDLE hJob = CreateJobObject (NULL, NULL);
     JOBOBJECT_EXTENDED_LIMIT_INFORMATION jeli;
     ZeroMemory(&jeli, sizeof(JOBOBJECT_EXTENDED_LIMIT_INFORMATION));
@@ -226,6 +232,7 @@ createJob ()

     maperrno();
     return NULL;
+#endif
 }

 /* Small helper function that determines how the std handle should be used.
